{"title_page": "Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean actress}}\n{{for|the actress of the same name|Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1972)}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Kim Min-hee\n| image        = 150917 Kim Min-hee vip cropped 1.jpg\n| caption      = Kim in 2015\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1982|3|1}}\n| birth_place  = [[Yejang-dong]], [[Jung District, Seoul]], South Korea\n| education    = [[Dankook University]] - [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in Theater and Film Studies<ref>[http://epg.epg.co.kr/star/profile/index.asp?actor_id=2356 \"\uae40\ubbfc\ud76c\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225063710/http://epg.epg.co.kr/star/profile/index.asp?actor_id=2356 |date=2012-02-25 }}. ''Epg'' (in Korean). Retrieved 2012-09-30.</ref>\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1999\u2013present\n| agent        = {{hlist|[[Management SOOP]]|Forest Entertainment}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title        = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul       = \uae40\ubbfc\ud76c\n| hanja        = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u654f|\u59ec}}\n| rr           = Gim Min-hui\n| mr           = Kim Minh\u016di \n}}\n\n'''Kim Min-hee''' (born March 1, 1982) is a South Korean actress and model.\n\n==Career==\nKim Min-hee began [[model (profession)|modeling]] when she was in middle school, and soon appeared as a cover girl in teen magazines. In 1999 she was cast in the campus drama ''School 2'' as a rebellious high school girl, which launched her to stardom. She became a popular young star at barely 20 years old, appearing in [[Korean drama|TV dramas]] and movies. However, a string of poor acting performances brought her negative criticism. Critics and viewers disparagingly called her an \"attractive but blank actress,\" more famous for being a fashion icon and actor [[Lee Jung-jae]]'s then-girlfriend.<ref name=miri />\n\nIn 2006, after reading the synopsis of TV series ''[[Goodbye Solo (TV series)|Goodbye Solo]]'', Kim knew that she wanted the role of Mi-ri more than anything, saying \"I was ready to do anything to play her.\" She begged renowned screenwriter [[Noh Hee-kyung]] to cast her, and though Noh turned her down five times, Kim would not give up, and her determination eventually convinced Noh to see her hidden potential. Vowing to start over from the bottom, Kim went through strict acting training which included basic vocal and respiratory exercises; she got a hold of the script before anyone else, and continued to analyze the role and practice every day. Kim said that until ''Goodbye Solo'', she hadn't been sure what to do with the rest of her life, but the drama made her feel that acting was her true calling, like she'd \"finally opened up the first page of the textbook.\" She received good reviews for her performance, and despite the drama's low ratings, the role transformed her career.<ref name=miri>Shin, Hae-in (16 March 2006). [http://www.hancinema.net/actress-kim-min-hee-enjoys-limelight-again-5510.html \"Actress Kim Min-hee enjoys limelight again\"]. ''[[The Korea Herald]] via [[Hancinema]]''. Retrieved 2012-11-18.</ref>\n\nHer succeeding movie roles helped solidify her career reinvention, beginning with 2008's ''[[Hellcats (film)|Hellcats]]'' (also known by its [[Korean language|Korean]] title ''I Like It Hot'' or ''Some Like It Hot''), a light-hearted comedy that explored the lives and loves of three women at different stages of womanhood. Kim played an aspiring screenwriter in her twenties who's agonizing over her insecure career and shaky romance with a deadbeat musician boyfriend. Reviews praised her \"compelling performance,\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Hyo-won |title=''Hellcats'' Is Charmingly Off-Tune |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/01/141_17459.html |work=[[The Korea Times]] |accessdate=2012-11-18 |date=27 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201174128/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/01/141_17459.html |archivedate= 1 February 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yang|first=Sung-jin|title=''Hellcats'' rejects men, holds girl-only party|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20080108000031|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=2012-12-19|date=8 January 2008}}</ref> and she later won Best Actress at the [[Baeksang Arts Awards]] and the [[Busan Film Critics Awards]].<ref name=baek1>{{cite web|title=The 44th PaekSang Arts Awards Sparkles with Stars|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/program/program_musicnews_detail.htm?lang=e&No=7468|work=[[KBS World]]|accessdate=2013-06-30|date=24 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nKim then joined the all-star cast of ''[[Actresses (film)|Actresses]]'' (2009), a semi-[[improvisational]] [[mockumentary]] directed by [[E J-yong]] (whom she had previously worked with in ''Asako in Ruby Shoes''). Set during a ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Korea]]'' photo shoot, Kim gets upset in the film over a remark by a staffer that men don't find skinny women like her attractive, as compared to her more voluptuous costar [[Kim Ok-bin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Hyo-won|title=Actresses to Present Off-Screen Personas Onscreen|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/11/141_55644.html|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=2013-05-28|date=17 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ji-hye|title=''Actresses'' is a miracle achieved, says Koh (Part 1)|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent8&idxno=2009112317360136554|work=10Asia|accessdate=2013-05-28|date=23 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ji-hye|title=''Actresses'' is a miracle achieved, says Koh (Part 2)|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent5&idxno=2009112323221892613|work=10Asia|accessdate=2013-05-28|date=23 November 2009}}</ref> A supporting turn as a reporter in conspiracy film ''Moby Dick'' followed in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Hyo-won |title=Conspiracy flick is painstakingly real |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/06/135_88194.html |work=[[The Korea Times]] |accessdate=2013-05-28 |date=2 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063054/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/06/135_88194.html |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hong|first=Lucia|title=Kim Min-hee cast as female lead in new thriller|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2011052410173049993|work=10Asia|accessdate=2013-05-28|date=24 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nKim further stretched the limits of her acting range in psychological thriller ''[[Helpless (2012 film)|Helpless]]'' (2012), [[film adaptation|adapted]] from [[Miyabe Miyuki]]'s novel ''[[All She Was Worth]]'' (in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], \"one-way train/fire chariot to hell\"). She said she had absolute trust in director [[Byun Young-joo]] and never even checked the monitors,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=In-kyung|title=Kim Min Hee Brings the Mystery for ''Train''|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=3028|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130130004456/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=3028|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2013|accessdate=2012-11-18|work=enewsWorld|date=29 January 2012}}</ref> and Byun was likewise complimentary, saying, \"I ended up adding more scenes for her to act because she was just exceptional. She knew what she was doing, and knew she was able to pull it off. She was rarely nervous throughout the production. She's got no fear and is always confident.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Claire|title=Director explores financial, social horrors|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20120308001013|accessdate=2012-11-18|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=8 March 2012}}</ref> Kim said the role gave her a chance to show what she was capable of as an actress, adding, \"I feel differently about acting now. I often feel a tremendous sense of achievement and really enjoy doing this job.\"<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/03/03/2012030300341.html \"Kim Min-hee Anything But ''Helpless'' in New Movie Role\"]. ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]''. 3 March 2012. Retrieved 2012-11-18.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Nancy|title=Kim Min Hee Thinks Happiness is Close By|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=3597|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129022929/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=3597|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2013|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=2012-11-18|date=16 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Jin-ho|title=Interview: Kim Min Hee was Always Confident about Her Acting|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=4186|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129015811/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=4186|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2013|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=2012-11-18|date=10 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Jin-ho|title=Kim Min Hee Opens Up About Love and Future|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=4271|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129015454/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=4271|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2013|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=2012-11-18|date=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Son|first=Hye-young|title=Kim Min Hee, The Cherry Blossom Girl|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=28728|work=1st Look Magazine via enewsWorld|accessdate=2013-02-13|date=11 February 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411092153/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=28728|archive-date=11 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Displaying a striking screen presence as a mysterious girl who disappears without a trace while her bewildered fianc\u00e9 discovers a trail of falsified information, Kim received several acting nominations and won Best Actress at the [[Buil Film Awards]].<ref name=buil /> \n\nAfter her contract with [[Lee Byung-hun]]'s agency BH Entertainment ended in late 2012, Kim signed with Management Soop, which also handles the career of her friend [[Gong Hyo-jin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Tae-ho|title=Kim Min-hee signs exclusive contract with Gong Yoo's agency|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2012081419143515432|accessdate=2012-11-18|work=10Asia|date=14 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kim again earned raves for her performance in ''[[Very Ordinary Couple]]''. Unlike the typical romantic comedy, the relationship drama told a more realistic story of an on-and-off couple of three years.<ref>{{cite web|last=An|first=So-hyoun|title=Kim Min Hee Says She's Honest in Love Relationships|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=30328|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411102246/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=30328|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 April 2013|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=2013-03-04|date=3 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Han|first=Jae-hee|title=Kim stretches her acting chops|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2969580|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=2013-05-28|date=4 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409022112/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2969580|archivedate=9 April 2013}}</ref> During her acceptance speech as Best Actress at the [[49th Paeksang Arts Awards|2013 Baeksang Arts Awards]], Kim thanked her costar [[Lee Min-ki]] and director [[Roh Deok]], who \"helped shape (her) character Young on the screen.\"<ref name=baek2>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Claire|title=Ryu Seung-ryong wins top prize at Paeksang|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20130510000642|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=2013-05-10|date=10 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Hye-ji|title=On the Scene: 2013 Paeksang Arts Awards: He Said, She Said|url=http://www.tenasia.com/on-the-scene-2013-paeksang-arts-awards-he-said-she-said/|work=10Asia|accessdate=2013-05-10|date=10 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145815/http://www.tenasia.com/on-the-scene-2013-paeksang-arts-awards-he-said-she-said/|archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref> [[Action film|Action]]-[[film noir|noir]] ''[[No Tears for the Dead]]'' followed in 2014, in which she played a grieving woman who becomes a hitman's target.\n\nKim next starred in [[Hong Sang-soo]]'s critically acclaimed film ''[[Right Now, Wrong Then]]'' (2015), which won her Best Actress at the [[Busan Film Critics Awards]].<ref name=busan>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3703|title=YOO Hae-jin and KIM Min-hee Take Acting Honors|date=16 December 2015|work=[[Korean Film Council]]}}</ref> Kim shot to international stardom for her performance in the award-winning film ''[[The Handmaiden]]'', [[Park Chan-wook]]'s 2016 film adaptation of ''[[Fingersmith (novel)|Fingersmith]]'' set in [[Korea under Japanese rule|1930s Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=June|title=KIM Min-hee and KIM Tae-ri Confirmed for FINGERSMITH|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3255|website=Korean Film Biz Zone|accessdate=2014-12-12|date=10 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/02/251_224554.html|title=Actress wearing 'invisible' scarlet letter|work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=23 February 2017}}</ref> Park called her \"the most coveted a-list actress at the moment.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jin|first1=Eun-soo|title=''The Handmaiden'' generates a buzz|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3018243|website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=2016-05-10|date=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Kim became the first Korean actress to win the [[Berlin Film Festival Award for Best Actress|Silver Bear for Best Actress]] at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] for her performance in the film ''[[On the Beach at Night Alone]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2017/02/689_224289.html|title=Kim Min-hee wins best actress award in Berlin film festival |date=19 February 2017|work=[[The Korea Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Hong Sangsoo and Kim Minhee, 2017.jpg|thumb|250px|Hong Sang-soo and Kim Min-hee admitted to their affair at a press conference.]]\n\nIn June 2016, Kim was reported to be having an affair with [[Hong Sang-soo]], the director of the film ''[[Right Now, Wrong Then]]'', in which she starred as the lead actress in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/02/251_224554.html|title=Actress wearing 'invisible' scarlet letter|date=23 February 2017|work=[[The Korea Times]]}}</ref> At the Seoul premiere of ''[[On the Beach at Night Alone]]'' in March 2017, Kim and Hong openly admitted their affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/03/14/2017031401300.html|title=Hong Sang-soo Speaks About Romance with Star|date=14 March 2017|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2000 || ''Asako in Ruby Shoes'' || Mia\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Surprise Party'' || Hwang Mi-ryung \n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Hellcats (film)|Hellcats]]'' || Ami\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Actresses (film)|Actresses]]'' || Kim Min-hee\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Moby Dick'' || Sung Hyo-kwan \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Helpless (2012 film)|Helpless]]'' || Kang Sun-young \n|-\n| rowspan=2|2013 || ''Behind the Camera'' ||\n|-\n| ''[[Very Ordinary Couple]]'' || Jang Young \n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[No Tears for the Dead]]'' || Mo-kyung \n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Right Now, Wrong Then]]'' || Yoon Hee-jung \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Handmaiden]]'' || Lady Hideko \n|-\n| rowspan=3| 2017 || ''[[On the Beach at Night Alone]]'' || Young-hee\n|-\n| ''[[Claire's Camera]]'' || Jeon Man-hee\n|-\n| ''[[The Day After (2017 film)|The Day After]]'' || Song Ah-reum\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Grass (2018 film)|Grass]]'' || 