len}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Laetare Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Cuernavaca]]\n[[Category:People from Morelos]]\n[[Category:People from Nyack, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography and Awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Hayes"}
{"title_page": "Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 2006", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish legislation (2006)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Politics of Catalonia}}\n\nThe '''Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 2006''' ({{lang-ca|Estatut d\u2019Autonomia de Catalunya}}) provides Catalonia's basic institutional regulations under the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]]. It defines the rights and obligations of the citizens of [[Catalonia]], the political institutions of the Catalan community, their competences and relations with the rest of [[Spain]], and the financing of the [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Government of Catalonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.gencat.cat/ca/inici/ |title=Official web of the Generalitat de Catalunya |publisher=Gencat.net |date=18 June 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nThis Law was approved by [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum]] on 18 June 2006 and supplanted the first [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979|Statute of Sau]], which dated from 1979. The approval was given by the 36% of Catalan people with the right to vote. Abstention in the referendum was high: more than 50%.<ref>{{citation | title = El Estatut sale adelante, pero la participaci\u00f3n no llega al 50% | url = https://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2006/06/18/espana/1150653842.html | publisher = El Mundo | date = 19 June 2006}}.</ref> On 28 June 2010, the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] assessed the constitutionality of several articles of the Law,<ref>{{citation | title = El Tribunal Constitucional dicta sentencia sobre el Estatut | url = http://www.elperiodico.com/es/noticias/politica/tribunal-constitucional-dicta-sentencia-sobre-estatut-354031 | publisher = El Peri\u00f3dico | date = 28 June 2010}}.</ref> rewriting 14 of them and dictating the interpretation for 27 more. That led to a [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest|massive demonstration in Barcelona]] of more than a million people<ref>{{citation | title = Catalan protesters rally for greater autonomy in Spain | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/10588494.stm | publisher = BBC News | date = 10 July 2010}}.</ref><ref>{{citation | title = More than 1 million protest court ruling in Barcelona | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/11/spain.protests/index.html | publisher = CNN | date = 11 July 2010}}.</ref> under the slogan in Catalan ''Som una naci\u00f3. Nosaltres decidim'' (in English, \"We are a nation. We decide\").\n\n==History==\nIn 1919, a first [[Statute of Catalonia of 1919|project of Statute]] was started by the [[Commonwealth of Catalonia]] although it was rejected by Spanish ''[[Cortes Generales]]''.\n\nIn 1928, a [[Draft Constitution of the Catalan Republic of 1928|project of Constitution]] was written in [[Havana]] by exiled Catalan nationalists.\n\nCatalonia first obtained a [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1932|Statute of Autonomy in 1932]], during the [[Second Spanish Republic]]. This law was abolished by General [[Francisco Franco]] after the [[Spanish Civil War]], largely because Catalonia had been a region generally opposed to Franco's ''Nacionales'' forces. During periods of his rule, public usage of the Catalan language and culture, and more specifically, Catalan self-government were harshly suppressed.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}}.\n\nIn 1979, during the [[Spanish transition to democracy]], the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979|second Statute]] was approved by referendum.\n\nOn 18 June 2006, a [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum]] amending the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979]] to further expand the authority of the Generalitat de Catalunya, Catalonia's government, was approved, and became effective on 9 August 2006.\n\nThis referendum was noted for its [[voter turnout]] being below 50%.\nIt was also noted for its uneasy coalition forging. Tensions within the coalition government which originally promoted the Statute led to an [[2006 Catalan Parliament election|early regional election in 2006]].\n\n===2005 Draft===\nThe \"Draft of New Statute of Autonomy for Catalonia of 2005\" was a [[reform]] proposal regarding Catalan self-government.\n\nOn 30 September 2005, the [[Catalan Parliament]] approved (with the support of 120 [[Member of Parliament|deputies]] to 15) a proposal for reform of the current [[Statute of Autonomy]]. The approved proposal was sent for review and discussion to the [[Cortes Generales]] (Spain's parliament) on 2 November 2005.\n\nAfter receiving the proposal drafted by the Catalan regional parliament, on 2 November 2005 the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Spanish Congress of Deputies]] approved the admission to formality of the ''Proposal for reform of the new Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia'' with the support of all the groups except the [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party (PP)]]. The latter filed an objection of unconstitutionality before the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]], which ruled unconstitutional 14 articles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribunalconstitucional.es/es/jurisprudencia/paginas/Sentencia.aspx?cod=16273|title=Detalle de sentencia|work=tribunalconstitucional.es|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204071339/http://www.tribunalconstitucional.es/es/jurisprudencia/Paginas/Sentencia.aspx?cod=16273|archive-date=4 December 2012|df=}}</ref> of the original text. Its [[constitutionality]] has also been contested by some intellectuals and [[journalist]]s related to liberal or conservative media such as the [[COPE (radio station)|COPE (Catholic radio network)]] and the Madrid-based [[newspaper]]s ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' and ''[[La Raz\u00f3n (Madrid)|La Raz\u00f3n]]''.\n\nOn 21 January 2006, [[Spanish Prime Minister]] [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]] and Catalan [[Opposition (parliamentary)|Leader of the Opposition]] [[Artur Mas]] arrived at a pre-agreement about nation definition and financing in the current project of statute.\n\nOn 10 May 2006, the amended text<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060725070939/http://www.gencat.net/nouestatut/cat/estatut_textsenat_cat.pdf]</ref> passed through its final reading through both Houses of the [[Cortes Generales|Parliament]], with the support of all parties except both the Spanish main opposition party, the conservative People's Party, and the [[Catalan separatism|Catalan separatist]] party [[Esquerra Republicana de Catalunya]]. The latter voted against the project in the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Spanish Congress of Deputies]] but abstained in the [[Spanish Senate|Senate]] (to avoid a blocking vote). ERC voted against it, despite its senior members having had a hand in drafting its content, as a result of the internal tensions within the party which this issue had brought to the surface. Later on both parties, for opposite reasons, supported a ''no'' vote in the [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum held afterwards regarding the passing of the new Statute]].\n\nThe [[List of Presidents of Catalonia|president of Catalonia]], [[Pasqual Maragall]], decided that Sunday 18 June would be the date on which the text would be put to the [[Catalan people]] in the form of a [[referendum]]. The referendum approved the Statute, the \"yes\" side receiving 74% of [[votes]] cast. The [[voter turnout]] was 49.41% of the total [[constituency|electorate]], an unprecedentedly low figure for this type of vote. The new Statute has been in force since 9 August 2006.\n\n===Data===\n* The [[1931 Catalan autonomy referendum|1931 referendum]] on the Statute of Autonomy registered a [[voter turnout]] of 75.13%, of which 99.49% voted favourably to its passing, according to the official results released.\n* The [[1979 Catalan autonomy referendum|1979 referendum]] on the Statute of Autonomy registered a voter turnout of 59.7%, of which 88.1% voted favorably.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paco Soto/Barcelona |url=http://www.hoy.es/pg060619/prensa/noticias/Nacional/200606/19/HOY-NAC-092.html |title=Hoy Digital &#124; NACIONAL&nbsp;\u2013 El nuevo Estatut catal\u00e1n cosecha el menor respaldo de la historia |publisher=Hoy.es |date=1 December 1997 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|2006 referendum]] on the current version of the Statute registered a voter turnout of 48.85%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/132031/0/estatut/referendum/reacciones/ |title=Reacciones pol\u00edticas al \"S\u00ed\" de los catalanes al Estatut empa\u00f1ado por el bajo \u00edndice de participaci\u00f3n |publisher=20minutos.es |date=18 June 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Of the total votes, 73.24% were in favour of the new Statute, while 20.57% were against.\n\n==Self-government under the statute==\nCatalonia is an [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Community]] within the Kingdom of [[Spain]], with the status of [[Nationalities and regions of Spain|historical region]] in the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]]. In September 2005, the [[Parliament of Catalonia]] approved the definition of Catalonia as a 'nation' in the [[preamble]]<ref>[http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/preambul.htm Preamble of the ''Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080708213233/http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/preambul.htm |date=8 July 2008}}, Generalitat of Catalonia</ref> of the new Statute of Autonomy (autonomous basic law).\n\nThe 120 delegates of all parties (CiU, PSC, ERC, ICV-EA) with the exception of the 15 delegates of the Partido Popular approved this definition.\nIn the opinion of the Spanish Government this has a 'declaratory' but not a 'legal' value, since the Spanish Constitution recognises the indissoluble \"unity of the Spanish Nation\".\n\nThe [[Generalitat de Catalunya]] is the institution in which the self-government of Catalonia is politically organised. It consists of the [[Parliament of Catalonia|Parliament]], the [[President of the Generalitat de Catalunya|President of the Generalitat]], and the Executive Council or [[Government of Catalonia]].\n\nThe Statute of Autonomy gives the Generalitat of Catalonia the powers that enable it to carry out the functions of self-government. These can be exclusive, concurrent, and shared with the Spanish State or executives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/titol_4.htm |title=Competencies of the Generalitat&nbsp;\u2013 Official web |publisher=Gencat.net |date= |access-date=2010-07-12 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205155332/http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/titol_4.htm |archive-date=5 December 2008 |df= }}</ref> The Generalitat holds jurisdiction in various matters of culture, education, health, justice, environment, communications, transportation, commerce, public safety, and local governments. Catalonia has its own police force, the [[Mossos d'Esquadra]], although the Spanish government keep agents in the region for matters relating to border control, terrorism and immigration.\n\nMost of the justice system is administered by Spanish judicial institutions. The legal system is uniform throughout Spain, with the exception of so-called \"[[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]]\", which is administered separately within Catalonia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://civil.udg.es/normacivil/catalunya.htm |title=Legislaci\u00f3 civil catalana |publisher=Civil.udg.es |date=20 July 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Differences with the Statute of 1979===\nThe Statute of Autonomy of 2006 tried to consolidate and extend the self-government established by the Statute approved in 1979, most notably:<ref>[http://www.iceta.org/comp7906.pdf Comparativa entre l\u2019Estatut de 1979 i el nou Estatut] iceta.org</ref>\n\n* Catalonia is defined as a nation in the preambule of the text, while in the Article 1 the  definition remained as a \"nationality\", like in the 1979 Statute.\n* Regulation of the [[national symbols of Catalonia]]: [[Flag of Catalonia|flag]], [[Els Segadors|national anthem]], and [[National Day of Catalonia|national day]].\n* Introduction of historical rights as one of the basis of the self-government.\n* Reinforce of [[Catalan language]] as the own language of Catalonia, making it the main language of Catalan administration and introducing the duty of learn it, alongside Spanish. The [[Occitan language]] ([[Aranese dialect|Aranese]] in [[Val d'Aran]]) is declared an official language of Catalonia, as Catalan and Spanish were since the 1979 Statute.\n* Creation of an entire title (Title I) dedicated to the rights and obligations of Catalan citizens, apart from the ones of the Spanish Constitution.\n* Creation of [[Vegueries]] as the new territorial division of Catalonia, suppression of the four Spanish Provincial Deputations.\n* Reinforce of the powers of the [[High Court of Justice of Catalonia]]. Creation of the High Prosecutor of Catalonia and the Council of Justice of Catalonia.\n* New competences of the Generalitat and better definition of them. New powers over:\n** Religious entities\n** Landscapes\n** Popular consultations, except referendums\n** Maritime safety\n** Attention and initial support for immigrants\n** Transportation that circulates entirely through Catalan territory\n** [[Labour inspection]]\n** etc.\n* Establishment of bilateral relations between the Generalitat and Spanish Government.\n* Definition of foreign actions of Catalonia. Possibility of creation of delegations of the Generalitat abroad.\n* Extension of powers in matter of financing:\n** Creation of the Tax Agency of Catalonia, which collects and manages the own taxes of the Generalitat and those totally granted by the State\n** Increase in participation of State taxes (IRPF, IVA, Society tax)\n** Regulation of state investments in Catalonia\n\n==Criticism==\nPolitical parties, such as [[Ciutadans|Cs]] and [[People's Party (Spain)|PP]] have pointed out what they describe as an \"identity obsession\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2006/11/01/espana/1162413118.html |title=Euforia entre los simpatizantes de Ciutadans por la entrada en el Parlament |publisher=elmundo.es |date=16 September 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> amongst [[Catalan nationalist]] politicians and the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] media establishment. They quote the unprecedentedly high [[abstention]] in the [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum regarding the Statute]] as a symptom of those cited sectors being out of sync with the populace at large. On the opposite side, Catalan nationalists, such as [[Convergence and Union|CiU]], [[Republican Left of Catalonia]] (ERC), or [[Popular Unity Candidature|CUP]], think that the Statute does not give Catalonia sufficient self-government after it was modified by the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.publico.es/espana/324515/el-constitucional-amputa-parte-del-estatut | title=El Constitucional amputa parte del Estatut |publisher=publico.es |date=29 June 2006 |accessdate=14 September 2010}}</ref> They claim the Statute that was brought to referendum differed substantially from the one the Constitutional Court delivered on points considered key by these parties,<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2010/06/28/barcelona/1277749604.html |title= CiU tilda de 'grav\u00edsima' la 'situaci\u00f3n generada por la sentencia' del Estatut |publisher=elmundo.es |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> starting the first massive [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest|Catalan demonstrations]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2010/07/10/barcelona/1278761492.html |title=Masiva manifestaci\u00f3n en Barcelona en apoyo al Estatut y contra el Constitucional |publisher=elmundo.es |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> in favor of the [[Catalan independence]].\n\n==Legal challenge and the Catalans' response==\nThe Statute has been legally contested by the surrounding [[Autonomous Communities]] of Aragon, Balearic Islands, and the Valencian Community,<ref>{{cite web|author=Europa Press/Madrid |url=http://www.hoy.es/prensa/20061115/nacional/admitidos-recursos-aragon-valencia_20061115.html |title=Admitidos los recursos de Arag\u00f3n, Valencia y Baleares contra el Estatuto catal\u00e1n. |publisher=hoy.es |date=1 December 1997 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> as well as by the [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]] (then the main opposition party at the Spanish Parliament). The objections are based on various topics such as disputed [[cultural heritage]] but, especially, on the Statute's alleged breaches of the \"solidarity between regions\" principle in fiscal and educational matters enshrined by the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]].\n\nThe Catalan political arena largely viewed this debate as a sort of cultural war waged by [[Spanish nationalism|\"Spanish nationalists\"]] (''espanyolistes'' in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]). In response, four of the six political parties in the Catalan parliament ([[Convergence and Union]], [[Socialists' Party of Catalonia|the Catalan Socialists]], [[Republican Left of Catalonia]], and [[Initiative for Catalonia Greens|Catalan green party]]), which that represented 88% of the popular, agreed to fight together in the [[Spanish Senate]] to reform the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] to try to keep overturn of the Catalan Statute of Autonomy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.directe.cat/noticia/35961/tripartit-i-ciu-pacten-una-proposta-per-reformar-el-tc-espanyol-i-aturar-la-sentencia-sobr|title=Tripartit i CiU pacten una proposta per reformar el TC espanyol i aturar la sent\u00e8ncia sobre l'Estatut|work=directe!cat|access-date=12 October 2017|language=ca}}</ref> The pact was particularly interesting because, aside from the fact that they all pertain to various degrees of [[Catalan nationalism]], the four parties differ greatly in political ideology and together form nearly 80% of the [[Catalan Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parlament.cat/web/composicio/distribucio-escons |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624140339/http://www.parlament.cat/web/composicio/distribucio-escons |archive-date=24 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> However, this attempt was largely unsuccessful.\n\nAfter four years of deliberations, the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] assessed the constitutionality of the challenged articles and its binding assessment was released on 28 June 2010. By a 6 to 4 majority, the Court's justices rewrote 14 articles and dictated the interpretation for 27 more, mainly those relating to language, justice and fiscal policy. The judgement reassured that the term \"nation\" used in the preamble has no legal standing. It also abolished all the mechanisms that had been put in place to minimize the distortionary effects of the existing Spanish tax and transfer system.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20100628/53954106148/el-tc-rebaja-las-aspiraciones-de-catalunya-en-lengua-justicia-y-tributos-catalanes.html |title=El TC rebaja las aspiraciones de Catalunya en lengua, justicia y tributos catalanes |publisher=lavanguardia.com |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> The legitimacy of the decision has been widely questioned in Catalonia: the term of three of the twelve members of the Court had already expired when a decision had been made; a fourth member had died and the Spanish Parliament had not appointed any successor.\n\nFollowing the decision of the Constitutional Court, Catalan public opinion grew increasingly favorable to hold a referendum to decide whether Catalonia should become an independent state from Spain. By September 2013, polls show different numbers according to the surveyor. According to the Spanish Agency (Centro de Investigaciones Sociol\u00f3gicas), there would be 40.6% of Catalans in favor of independence and 25.7% in favor of achieving more self-government, while 17.6% would be happy in the current situation and 9.1% of them would prefer to have less autonomy.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/07/10/barcelona/1373455086.html |title=El 40% de los catalanes quiere la independencia, seg\u00fan el CIS |publisher=elmundo.es |date=10 July 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> According to the Catalan Agency (Centre d'Estudis d'Opini\u00f3), in the event of a referendum there would have been 55.6% of Catalans in favor of independence and 23.4% of them voting against it.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elperiodico.com/es/noticias/politica/independencia-ganaria-556-referendo-2427055 |title=La independencia ganar\u00eda por un 55% seg\u00fan el CEO |publisher=elPeriodico.com |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> The remaining percentages in either poll were still undecided. More recent polls in 2017 have suggested that support for independence has gone down slowly and steadily from its peak in 2012\u201313, with only 41% in favor of independence vs 49% against it.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/07/21/inenglish/1500633835_182589.html |title=Support for an independent Catalonia declining, new poll shows |publisher=elpais.com |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> Regardless of the polls, when it came to the referendum, where, despite an estimated 770,000 votes being confiscated by the police, the voters overwhelmingly supported independence: 90.18% voting in favor, and only 7.83% voting against.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212613/http://www.govern.cat/pres_gov/govern/ca/monografics/303541/govern-trasllada-resultats-definitius-referendum-l1-doctubre-parlament-catalunya.html |title=Resultats del referendum de l'1 d'octubre |publisher=govern.cat |date=2 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Catalonia]]\n* [[Generalitat de Catalunya]]\n* [[Autonomous communities of Spain]]\n* [[Spanish transition to democracy]]\n* [[Statute of Autonomy]]\n* [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parlament.cat/document/cataleg/150259.pdf Full text of the 2006 Statute] (in [[PDF]])\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/5091572.stm Catalonia endorses autonomy plan] BBC News. 19 June 2006.\n* Text of the 2005 [https://web.archive.org/web/20140224115212/http://www.parlament.cat/porteso/estatut/estatut_english.pdf ''Proposal for reform of the new Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia''] (in [[PDF]])\n* [http://www.diplocat.cat/images/doc/SERIE-E-2013-5-1-EN-20130709.pdf The controversial reform of the Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]\n\n{{Statute of Catalonia}}\n\n[[Category:2006 in Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Statutes of Autonomy of Catalonia|2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish legislation (2006)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Politics of Catalonia}}\n\nThe '''Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 2006''' ({{lang-ca|Estatut d\u2019Autonomia de Catalunya}}) provides Catalonia's basic institutional regulations under the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]]. It defines the rights and obligations of the citizens of [[Catalonia]], the political institutions of the Catalan community, their competences and relations with the rest of [[Spain]], and the financing of the [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Government of Catalonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.gencat.cat/ca/inici/ |title=Official web of the Generalitat de Catalunya |publisher=Gencat.net |date=18 June 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nThis Law was approved by [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum]] on 18 June 2006 and supplanted the first [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979|Statute of Sau]], which dated from 1979. The approval was given by the 36% of Catalan people with the right to vote. Abstention in the referendum was high: more than 50%.<ref>{{citation | title = El Estatut sale adelante, pero la participaci\u00f3n no llega al 50% | url = https://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2006/06/18/espana/1150653842.html | publisher = El Mundo | date = 19 June 2006}}.</ref> On 28 June 2010, the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] assessed the constitutionality of several articles of the Law,<ref>{{citation | title = El Tribunal Constitucional dicta sentencia sobre el Estatut | url = http://www.elperiodico.com/es/noticias/politica/tribunal-constitucional-dicta-sentencia-sobre-estatut-354031 | publisher = El Peri\u00f3dico | date = 28 June 2010}}.</ref> rewriting 14 of them and dictating the interpretation for 27 more. That led to a [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest|massive demonstration in Barcelona]] of more than a million people<ref>{{citation | title = Catalan protesters rally for greater autonomy in Spain | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/10588494.stm | publisher = BBC News | date = 10 July 2010}}.</ref><ref>{{citation | title = More than 1 million protest court ruling in Barcelona | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/11/spain.protests/index.html | publisher = CNN | date = 11 July 2010}}.</ref> under the slogan in Catalan ''Som una naci\u00f3. Nosaltres decidim'' (in English, \"We are a nation. We decide\").\n\n==History==\nIn 1919, a first [[Statute of Catalonia of 1919|project of Statute]] was started by the [[Commonwealth of Catalonia]] although it was rejected by Spanish ''[[Cortes Generales]]''.\n\nIn 1928, a [[Draft Constitution of the Catalan Republic of 1928|project of Constitution]] was written in [[Havana]] by exiled Catalan nationalists.\n\nCatalonia first obtained a [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1932|Statute of Autonomy in 1932]], during the [[Second Spanish Republic]]. This law was abolished by General [[Francisco Franco]] after the [[Spanish Civil War]], largely because Catalonia had been a region generally opposed to Franco's ''Nacionales'' forces. During periods of his rule, public usage of the Catalan language and culture, and more specifically, Catalan self-government were harshly suppressed.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}}.\n\nIn 1979, during the [[Spanish transition to democracy]], the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979|second Statute]] was approved by referendum.\n\nOn 18 June 2006, a [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum]] amending the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1979]] to further expand the authority of the Generalitat de Catalunya, Catalonia's government, was approved, and became effective on 9 August 2006.\n\nThis referendum was noted for its [[voter turnout]] being below 50%.\nIt was also noted for its uneasy coalition forging. Tensions within the coalition government which originally promoted the Statute led to an [[2006 Catalan Parliament election|early regional election in 2006]].\n\n===2005 Draft===\nThe \"Draft of New Statute of Autonomy for Catalonia of 2005\" was a [[reform]] proposal regarding Catalan self-government.\n\nOn 30 September 2005, the [[Catalan Parliament]] approved (with the support of 120 [[Member of Parliament|deputies]] to 15) a proposal for reform of the current [[Statute of Autonomy]]. The approved proposal was sent for review and discussion to the [[Cortes Generales]] (Spain's parliament) on 2 November 2005.\n\nAfter receiving the proposal drafted by the Catalan regional parliament, on 2 November 2005 the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Spanish Congress of Deputies]] approved the admission to formality of the ''Proposal for reform of the new Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia'' with the support of all the groups except the [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party (PP)]]. The latter filed an objection of unconstitutionality before the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]], which ruled unconstitutional 14 articles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribunalconstitucional.es/es/jurisprudencia/paginas/Sentencia.aspx?cod=16273|title=Detalle de sentencia|work=tribunalconstitucional.es|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204071339/http://www.tribunalconstitucional.es/es/jurisprudencia/Paginas/Sentencia.aspx?cod=16273|archive-date=4 December 2012|df=}}</ref> of the original text. Its [[constitutionality]] has also been contested by some intellectuals and [[journalist]]s related to liberal or conservative media such as the [[COPE (radio station)|COPE (Catholic radio network)]] and the Madrid-based [[newspaper]]s ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' and ''[[La Raz\u00f3n (Madrid)|La Raz\u00f3n]]''.\n\nOn 21 January 2006, [[Spanish Prime Minister]] [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]] and Catalan [[Opposition (parliamentary)|Leader of the Opposition]] [[Artur Mas]] arrived at a pre-agreement about nation definition and financing in the current project of statute.\n\nOn 10 May 2006, the amended text<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060725070939/http://www.gencat.net/nouestatut/cat/estatut_textsenat_cat.pdf]</ref> passed through its final reading through both Houses of the [[Cortes Generales|Parliament]], with the support of all parties except both the Spanish main opposition party, the conservative People's Party, and the [[Catalan separatism|Catalan separatist]] party [[Esquerra Republicana de Catalunya]]. The latter voted against the project in the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Spanish Congress of Deputies]] but abstained in the [[Spanish Senate|Senate]] (to avoid a blocking vote). ERC voted against it, despite its senior members having had a hand in drafting its content, as a result of the internal tensions within the party which this issue had brought to the surface. Later on both parties, for opposite reasons, supported a ''no'' vote in the [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum held afterwards regarding the passing of the new Statute]].\n\nThe [[List of Presidents of Catalonia|president of Catalonia]], [[Pasqual Maragall]], decided that Sunday 18 June would be the date on which the text would be put to the [[Catalan people]] in the form of a [[referendum]]. The referendum approved the Statute, the \"yes\" side receiving 74% of [[votes]] cast. The [[voter turnout]] was 49.41% of the total [[constituency|electorate]], an unprecedentedly low figure for this type of vote. The new Statute has been in force since 9 August 2006.\n\n===Data===\n* The [[1931 Catalan autonomy referendum|1931 referendum]] on the Statute of Autonomy registered a [[voter turnout]] of 75.13%, of which 99.49% voted favourably to its passing, according to the official results released.\n* The [[1979 Catalan autonomy referendum|1979 referendum]] on the Statute of Autonomy registered a voter turnout of 59.7%, of which 88.1% voted favorably.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paco Soto/Barcelona |url=http://www.hoy.es/pg060619/prensa/noticias/Nacional/200606/19/HOY-NAC-092.html |title=Hoy Digital &#124; NACIONAL&nbsp;\u2013 El nuevo Estatut catal\u00e1n cosecha el menor respaldo de la historia |publisher=Hoy.es |date=1 December 1997 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|2006 referendum]] on the current version of the Statute registered a voter turnout of 48.85%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/132031/0/estatut/referendum/reacciones/ |title=Reacciones pol\u00edticas al \"S\u00ed\" de los catalanes al Estatut empa\u00f1ado por el bajo \u00edndice de participaci\u00f3n |publisher=20minutos.es |date=18 June 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Of the total votes, 73.24% were in favour of the new Statute, while 20.57% were against.\n\n==Self-government under the statute==\nCatalonia is an [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Community]] within the Kingdom of [[Spain]], with the status of [[Nationalities and regions of Spain|historical region]] in the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]]. In September 2005, the [[Parliament of Catalonia]] approved the definition of Catalonia as a 'nation' in the [[preamble]]<ref>[http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/preambul.htm Preamble of the ''Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080708213233/http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/preambul.htm |date=8 July 2008}}, Generalitat of Catalonia</ref> of the new Statute of Autonomy (autonomous basic law).\n\nThe 120 delegates of all parties (CiU, PSC, ERC, ICV-EA) with the exception of the 15 delegates of the Partido Popular approved this definition.\nIn the opinion of the Spanish Government this has a 'declaratory' but not a 'legal' value, since the Spanish Constitution recognises the indissoluble \"unity of the Spanish Nation\".\n\nThe [[Generalitat de Catalunya]] is the institution in which the self-government of Catalonia is politically organised. It consists of the [[Parliament of Catalonia|Parliament]], the [[President of the Generalitat de Catalunya|President of the Generalitat]] and the Executive Council or [[Government of Catalonia]].\n\nThe Statute of Autonomy gives the Generalitat of Catalonia the powers which enable it to carry out the functions of self-government. These can be exclusive, concurrent and shared with the Spanish State or executives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/titol_4.htm |title=Competencies of the Generalitat&nbsp;\u2013 Official web |publisher=Gencat.net |date= |access-date=2010-07-12 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205155332/http://www.gencat.net/generalitat/eng/estatut/titol_4.htm |archive-date=5 December 2008 |df= }}</ref> The Generalitat holds jurisdiction in various matters of culture, education, health, justice, environment, communications, transportation, commerce, public safety and local governments. Catalonia has its own police force, the [[Mossos d'Esquadra]], although the Spanish government keep agents in the region for matters relating to border control, terrorism and immigration.\n\nMost of the justice system is administered by Spanish judicial institutions. The legal system is uniform throughout Spain, with the exception of so-called \"[[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]]\", which is administered separately within Catalonia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://civil.udg.es/normacivil/catalunya.htm |title=Legislaci\u00f3 civil catalana |publisher=Civil.udg.es |date=20 July 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Differences with the Statute of 1979===\nThe Statute of Autonomy of 2006 tried to consolidate and extend the self-government established by the Statute approved in 1979, most notably:<ref>[http://www.iceta.org/comp7906.pdf Comparativa entre l\u2019Estatut de 1979 i el nou Estatut] iceta.org</ref>\n\n* Catalonia is defined as a nation in the preambule of the text, while in the Article 1 the  definition remained as a \"nationality\", like in the 1979 Statute.\n* Regulation of the [[national symbols of Catalonia]]: [[Flag of Catalonia|flag]], [[Els Segadors|national anthem]] and [[National Day of Catalonia|national day]].\n* Introduction of historical rights as one of the basis of the self-government.\n* Reinforce of [[Catalan language]] as the own language of Catalonia, making it the main language of Catalan administration and introducing the duty of learn it, alongside Spanish. The [[Occitan language]] ([[Aranese dialect|Aranese]] in [[Val d'Aran]]) is declared an official language of Catalonia, as Catalan and Spanish were since the 1979 Statute.\n* Creation of an entire title (Title I) dedicated to the rights and obligations of Catalan citizens, apart from the ones of the Spanish Constitution.\n* Creation of [[Vegueries]] as the new territorial division of Catalonia, suppression of the four Spanish Provincial Deputations.\n* Reinforce of the powers of the [[High Court of Justice of Catalonia]]. Creation of the High Prosecutor of Catalonia and the Council of Justice of Catalonia.\n* New competences of the Generalitat and better definition of them. New powers over:\n** Religious entities\n** Landscapes\n** Popular consultations, except referendums\n** Maritime safety\n** Attention and initial support for immigrants\n** Transportation that circulates entirely through Catalan territory\n** [[Labour inspection]]\n** etc.\n* Establishment of bilateral relations between the Generalitat and Spanish Government.\n* Definition of foreign actions of Catalonia. Possibility of creation of delegations of the Generalitat abroad.\n* Extension of powers in matter of financing:\n** Creation of the Tax Agency of Catalonia, which collects and manages the own taxes of the Generalitat and those totally granted by the State\n** Increase in participation of State taxes (IRPF, IVA, Society tax)\n** Regulation of state investments in Catalonia\n\n==Criticism==\nPolitical parties, such as [[Ciutadans|Cs]] and [[People's Party (Spain)|PP]] have pointed out what they describe as an \"identity obsession\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2006/11/01/espana/1162413118.html |title=Euforia entre los simpatizantes de Ciutadans por la entrada en el Parlament |publisher=elmundo.es |date=16 September 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> amongst [[Catalan nationalist]] politicians and the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] media establishment. They quote the unprecedentedly high [[abstention]] in the [[2006 Catalan constitutional referendum|referendum regarding the Statute]] as a symptom of those cited sectors being out of sync with the populace at large. On the opposite side, Catalan nationalists, such as [[Convergence and Union|CiU]], [[Republican Left of Catalonia]] (ERC) or [[Popular Unity Candidature|CUP]], think that the Statute does not give Catalonia sufficient self-government after it was modified by the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.publico.es/espana/324515/el-constitucional-amputa-parte-del-estatut | title=El Constitucional amputa parte del Estatut |publisher=publico.es |date=29 June 2006 |accessdate=14 September 2010}}</ref> They claim the Statute that was brought to referendum differed substantially from the one the Constitutional Court delivered on points considered key by these parties,<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2010/06/28/barcelona/1277749604.html |title= CiU tilda de 'grav\u00edsima' la 'situaci\u00f3n generada por la sentencia' del Estatut |publisher=elmundo.es |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> starting the first massive [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest|Catalan demonstrations]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2010/07/10/barcelona/1278761492.html |title=Masiva manifestaci\u00f3n en Barcelona en apoyo al Estatut y contra el Constitucional |publisher=elmundo.es |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> in favor of the [[Catalan independence]].\n\n==Legal challenge and the Catalans' response==\nThe Statute has been legally contested by the surrounding [[Autonomous Communities]] of Aragon, Balearic Islands and the Valencian Community,<ref>{{cite web|author=Europa Press/Madrid |url=http://www.hoy.es/prensa/20061115/nacional/admitidos-recursos-aragon-valencia_20061115.html |title=Admitidos los recursos de Arag\u00f3n, Valencia y Baleares contra el Estatuto catal\u00e1n. |publisher=hoy.es |date=1 December 1997 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> as well as by the [[People's Party (Spain)|Partido Popular]] (then the main opposition party at the Spanish Parliament). The objections are based on various topics such as disputed [[cultural heritage]] but, especially, on the Statute's alleged breaches of the \"solidarity between regions\" principle in fiscal and educational matters enshrined by the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]].\n\nThe Catalan political arena largely viewed this debate as a sort of cultural war waged by [[Spanish nationalism|\"Spanish nationalists\"]] (''espanyolistes'' in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]). In response, four of the six political parties in the Catalan parliament ([[Convergence and Union]], [[Socialists' Party of Catalonia|the Catalan Socialists]], [[Republican Left of Catalonia]], and [[Initiative for Catalonia Greens|Catalan green party]]), which that represented 88% of the popular, agreed to fight together in the [[Spanish Senate]] to reform the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] to try to keep overturn of the Catalan Statute of Autonomy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.directe.cat/noticia/35961/tripartit-i-ciu-pacten-una-proposta-per-reformar-el-tc-espanyol-i-aturar-la-sentencia-sobr|title=Tripartit i CiU pacten una proposta per reformar el TC espanyol i aturar la sent\u00e8ncia sobre l'Estatut|work=directe!cat|access-date=12 October 2017|language=ca}}</ref> The pact was particularly interesting because, aside from the fact that they all pertain to various degrees of [[Catalan nationalism]], the four parties differ greatly in political ideology and together form nearly 80% of the [[Catalan Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parlament.cat/web/composicio/distribucio-escons |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624140339/http://www.parlament.cat/web/composicio/distribucio-escons |archive-date=24 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> However, this attempt was largely unsuccessful.\n\nAfter four years of deliberations, the [[Constitutional Court of Spain]] assessed the constitutionality of the challenged articles and its binding assessment was released on 28 June 2010. By a 6 to 4 majority, the Court's justices rewrote 14 articles and dictated the interpretation for 27 more, mainly those relating to language, justice and fiscal policy. The judgement reassured that the term \"nation\" used in the preamble has no legal standing. It also abolished all the mechanisms that had been put in place to minimize the distortionary effects of the existing Spanish tax and transfer system.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20100628/53954106148/el-tc-rebaja-las-aspiraciones-de-catalunya-en-lengua-justicia-y-tributos-catalanes.html |title=El TC rebaja las aspiraciones de Catalunya en lengua, justicia y tributos catalanes |publisher=lavanguardia.com |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> The legitimacy of the decision has been widely questioned in Catalonia: the term of three of the twelve members of the Court had already expired when a decision had been made; a fourth member had died and the Spanish Parliament had not appointed any successor.\n\nFollowing the decision of the Constitutional Court, Catalan public opinion grew increasingly favorable to hold a referendum to decide whether Catalonia should become an independent state from Spain. By September 2013, polls show different numbers according to the surveyor. According to the Spanish Agency (Centro de Investigaciones Sociol\u00f3gicas), there would be 40.6% of Catalans in favor of independence and 25.7% in favor of achieving more self-government, while 17.6% would be happy in the current situation and 9.1% of them would prefer to have less autonomy.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/07/10/barcelona/1373455086.html |title=El 40% de los catalanes quiere la independencia, seg\u00fan el CIS |publisher=elmundo.es |date=10 July 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> According to the Catalan Agency (Centre d'Estudis d'Opini\u00f3), in the event of a referendum there would have been 55.6% of Catalans in favor of independence and 23.4% of them voting against it.<ref>{{cite_web|url=http://www.elperiodico.com/es/noticias/politica/independencia-ganaria-556-referendo-2427055 |title=La independencia ganar\u00eda por un 55% seg\u00fan el CEO |publisher=elPeriodico.com |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> The remaining percentages in either poll were still undecided. More recent polls in 2017 have suggested that support for independence has gone down slowly and steadily from its peak in 2012\u201313, with only 41% in favor of independence vs 49% against it.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/07/21/inenglish/1500633835_182589.html |title=Support for an independent Catalonia declining, new poll shows |publisher=elpais.com |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> Regardless of the polls, when it came to the referendum, where, despite an estimated 770,000 votes being confiscated by the police, the voters overwhelmingly supported independence: 90.18% voting in favor, and only 7.83% voting against.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212613/http://www.govern.cat/pres_gov/govern/ca/monografics/303541/govern-trasllada-resultats-definitius-referendum-l1-doctubre-parlament-catalunya.html |title=Resultats del referendum de l'1 d'octubre |publisher=govern.cat |date=2 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Catalonia]]\n* [[Generalitat de Catalunya]]\n* [[Autonomous communities of Spain]]\n* [[Spanish transition to democracy]]\n* [[Statute of Autonomy]]\n* [[2010 Catalan autonomy protest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parlament.cat/document/cataleg/150259.pdf Full text of the 2006 Statute] (in [[PDF]])\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/5091572.stm Catalonia endorses autonomy plan] BBC News. 19 June 2006.\n* Text of the 2005 [https://web.archive.org/web/20140224115212/http://www.parlament.cat/porteso/estatut/estatut_english.pdf ''Proposal for reform of the new Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia''] (in [[PDF]])\n* [http://www.diplocat.cat/images/doc/SERIE-E-2013-5-1-EN-20130709.pdf The controversial reform of the Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]\n\n{{Statute of Catalonia}}\n\n[[Category:2006 in Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Statutes of Autonomy of Catalonia|2006]]\n", "name_user": "Longdongwong", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statute_of_Autonomy_of_Catalonia_of_2006"}
